  <h2 id="why-calibration-matters">Why Calibration Matters</h2>
  <p>Every screen displays pixels at a different density. A 13-inch laptop packs roughly 2,304,000 pixels into a small space, while a 32-inch monitor spreads about the same number across a much larger area. This means a pixel on the laptop is physically smaller than a pixel on the monitor. When an online ruler assumes a standard pixel density without adjustment, the measurements it shows are wrong.</p>
  <p>Without calibration, errors of 5% to 20% are common. A 5% error on a 10-inch measurement is half an inch &mdash; enough to make a shipping box seem suitable when it is not, or to cut a piece of material too short. Calibration eliminates this error by measuring your actual display and calculating the correct pixel-to-physical conversion.</p>
  <p>RulerKit's calibration takes under 30 seconds and requires no special equipment. You have three methods to choose from, each suited to different situations. Once calibrated, the setting is stored in your browser and persists until you change displays or clear your local data.</p>

  <h2 id="method-1-auto-detect">Method 1 — Auto-Detect Calibration</h2>
  <p>Auto-detect is the fastest method. RulerKit reads your display's EDID (Extended Display Identification Data) directly from your operating system. This data includes the manufacturer, model, and physical size of your monitor. The tool cross-references this information against a database of known displays to determine the exact PPI.</p>
  <p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>
  <ol>
    <li>Open RulerKit's ruler tool.</li>
    <li>Click the calibration button in the sidebar panel.</li>
    <li>Select "Auto-Detect" from the calibration options.</li>
    <li>Wait 2-3 seconds while the tool reads your display information.</li>
    <li>Confirm the detected screen size and resolution.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>Auto-detect works best on desktop monitors and laptops with standard display configurations. It may not detect custom-built monitors, external displays connected via certain adapters, or virtual machines. For those cases, use one of the manual methods below.</p>

  <h2 id="method-2-screen-diagonal">Method 2 — Screen Diagonal Calibration</h2>
  <p>If auto-detect does not work or you want to verify its results, the screen diagonal method is the most reliable manual approach. You provide your screen's advertised diagonal size and aspect ratio, and RulerKit calculates the exact width, height, and PPI.</p>
  <p><strong>Step-by-step instructions:</strong></p>
  <ol>
    <li>Find your monitor's advertised diagonal size. This is usually printed on the box, listed on the manufacturer's website, or shown in your operating system's display settings. Common sizes include 21.5, 24, 27, and 32 inches for monitors, and 13.3, 15.6, and 17.3 inches for laptops.</li>
    <li>Determine your screen's aspect ratio. Most modern displays are 16:9. Older monitors and some productivity displays use 16:10. Ultra-wide monitors use 21:9.</li>
    <li>Open RulerKit's calibration panel and select "Screen Diagonal."</li>
    <li>Enter the diagonal measurement in inches (or centimeters if your region uses metric).</li>
    <li>Select the aspect ratio from the dropdown menu.</li>
    <li>Click "Calculate" to set the calibration.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>This method is accurate to within 1% if you enter the correct numbers. The math RulerKit uses is based on the Pythagorean theorem: for a 16:9 display with a 24-inch diagonal, the width is calculated as cos(arctan(9/16)) &times; 24 = 20.9 inches, and the height is sin(arctan(9/16)) &times; 24 = 11.8 inches.</p>
  <p><strong>Where to find your screen's diagonal:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Settings &gt; System &gt; Display &gt; Advanced display. Look for the monitor name, then search for its specs online.</li>
    <li><strong>macOS:</strong> System Settings &gt; Displays. The monitor name is shown at the top.</li>
    <li><strong>Physical check:</strong> Look for a sticker on the back or bottom edge of the monitor. It often lists the model number and size.</li>
    <li><strong>Manufacturer website:</strong> Search your monitor model number on the manufacturer's site. The specifications page lists the diagonal size.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="method-3-credit-card">Method 3 — Credit Card Calibration</h2>
  <p>If you do not know your screen's diagonal and auto-detect fails, use a physical reference object. A standard credit or debit card works perfectly because they follow the ISO/IEC 7810 ID-1 standard: 85.60 mm by 53.98 mm (3.370 inches by 2.125 inches).</p>
  <p><strong>Step-by-step instructions:</strong></p>
  <ol>
    <li>Take a credit card, debit card, or any ID card that follows the standard size.</li>
    <li>Place it flat against your screen, aligned with the ruler's starting edge.</li>
    <li>Open RulerKit's calibration panel and select "Credit Card" or "Manual."</li>
    <li>Adjust the calibration slider until the on-screen ruler shows 85.6 mm (or 3.37 inches) at the card's opposite edge.</li>
    <li>Fine-tune the slider until the ruler ticks align perfectly with both edges of the card.</li>
    <li>Save the calibration.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>For best results, hold the card steady with one hand while adjusting with the other. If the ruler ticks do not align at both edges simultaneously, the card may not be positioned flat against the screen. Try placing it on a flat desk against the screen's base instead of holding it in the air.</p>
  <p>Other reference objects work too, as long as you know their exact dimensions:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>US dollar bill:</strong> 156 mm by 66.3 mm (6.14 inches by 2.61 inches)</li>
    <li><strong>A4 paper:</strong> 210 mm by 297 mm (8.27 inches by 11.69 inches)</li>
    <li><strong>US letter paper:</strong> 216 mm by 279 mm (8.5 inches by 11 inches)</li>
    <li><strong>Post-it note (standard):</strong> 76 mm by 76 mm (3 inches by 3 inches)</li>
  </ul>

