  <h2 id="how-ppi-affects-accuracy">How PPI Affects Accuracy</h2>
  <p>Pixels per inch (PPI) is the fundamental variable behind every online ruler. The tool draws a line that is, say, 96 pixels long and labels it as 1 inch. But if your screen has 110 PPI, those 96 pixels only cover 0.87 physical inches &mdash; a 13% error. If your screen has 72 PPI, those same 96 pixels cover 1.33 inches, a 33% error.</p>
  <p>Here is how different displays compare when using an uncalibrated ruler that assumes 96 PPI:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>24-inch 1920x1080 monitor (92 PPI):</strong> The ruler shows 1 inch where there is actually 1.04 inches. Error: +4%.</li>
    <li><strong>27-inch 3840x2160 monitor (163 PPI):</strong> The ruler shows 1 inch where there is actually 0.59 inches. Error: -41%.</li>
    <li><strong>15.6-inch 1920x1080 laptop (141 PPI):</strong> The ruler shows 1 inch where there is actually 0.68 inches. Error: -32%.</li>
    <li><strong>14-inch 2560x1600 laptop (216 PPI):</strong> The ruler shows 1 inch where there is actually 0.44 inches. Error: -56%.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>These numbers make it clear: calibration is not optional for accurate measurement. The good news is that once you calibrate, the ruler is accurate for every measurement you take on that screen, regardless of the unit you use. The PPI value is the same whether you are reading centimeters or inches.</p>

  <h2 id="troubleshooting">Troubleshooting Common Issues</h2>
  <p>Even with a straightforward calibration process, issues can arise. Here is how to handle the most common ones.</p>
  <h3>Calibration not saving between sessions</h3>
  <p>RulerKit stores calibration data in your browser's local storage. If you clear your browser cache, cookies, or site data, the calibration is lost. Privacy-focused browsers or extensions that auto-clear data on exit will also remove your calibration. To avoid this, add RulerKit to your browser's "keep cookies and site data" exception list, or simply recalibrate after clearing your browser data.</p>
  <h3>Switching between devices or monitors</h3>
  <p>Each display has its own PPI. When you move from your laptop screen to an external monitor, the calibration changes. RulerKit detects display changes and prompts you to recalibrate. If you use multiple monitors simultaneously, calibrate each one separately. The tool remembers individual calibrations per display as long as the EDID data remains consistent.</p>
  <h3>Browser differences</h3>
  <p>Most modern browsers handle screen measurements the same way, but there are edge cases. Firefox on Linux may report incorrect screen dimensions due to driver differences. Safari on macOS handles Retina display scaling differently than Chrome. If you get inconsistent results, try switching browsers as a test. RulerKit is tested and optimized for Chrome, Firefox, Safari, and Edge on their latest versions.</p>
  <h3>Calibration seems wrong with a physical reference</h3>
  <p>If you calibrate using a credit card but measurements still seem off, verify that the card is actually ISO/IEC 7810 standard size. Some store loyalty cards, membership cards, or novelty cards are slightly different sizes. Try measuring the card with a physical ruler first to confirm its dimensions. Also ensure the card is lying flat against the screen with no gap, and that your browser zoom is at 100%.</p>

  <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
