      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">How often should I recalibrate my online ruler?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">Only when your display setup changes. Recalibrate after connecting a new monitor, changing screen resolution, switching from laptop to external display, or after clearing your browser data. The calibration persists indefinitely otherwise.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Which calibration method is most accurate?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">The screen diagonal method is the most accurate manual approach with about &plusmn;0.5% error, provided you enter the correct diagonal size. Auto-detect is close behind at &plusmn;1-2%. Credit card calibration is convenient but depends on how precisely you align the card.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Does browser zoom affect calibration?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">Yes. Browser zoom changes how CSS pixels map to screen pixels. Always set your browser zoom to 100% before calibrating and measuring. RulerKit displays a visible warning if it detects non-default zoom levels.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Can I calibrate without knowing my screen size?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">Yes. Use the credit card method or auto-detect. Both work without you needing to know your screen's diagonal. The auto-detect method reads the information directly from your display's internal data.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">Does calibration carry over between different browsers on the same computer?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">No. Calibration data is stored in each browser's local storage independently. If you calibrate in Chrome, you need to calibrate separately in Firefox, Safari, or Edge. The process is quick and takes about 15 seconds per browser.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <h3 itemprop="name" class="text-base font-semibold">What if my credit card is a different size than the standard?</h3>
      <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
        <div itemprop="text" class="text-sm text-surface-600">Most credit, debit, and ID cards follow the ISO/IEC 7810 ID-1 standard (85.60 x 53.98 mm). If you are unsure, measure the card with a physical ruler first. Some loyalty cards and gift cards use slightly different dimensions. You can also use any object with known dimensions as your reference.</div>
